recordings.type: duet of male and female, female, male, song
recordings.rmk:
Pareja de cárabos cantando a dúo, emitiendo los mismos tonos macho y hembra, ya fuera de la época de reproducción. Estaban en los árboles de ribera que crecen a las orillas del río Guadalquivir. Nótese como no cantan realmente a dúo, en el sentido de responderse el uno al otro, si no que hembra y macho tienen su propio ritmo de canto y pausas, parece que de forma independiente el uno del otro, llegando unas veces a cantar a la vez, para luego ir desfasando de nuevo. Por tanto parece que los dos emiten ese canto dirigido a otras parejas, quizás estableciendo su territorio, más que una comunicación entre ambos.

  Pair of tawny owls singing in duet, making the same tones, both male and female, out of the breeding season. They were perching in the riverbank trees of Guadalquivir river. Note here they don't sing really in a duet, in the sense of replying one another, but male and female have their own rhythm of tones and pauses independently, so they can reach a moment in which they sing at the same times, and after a few calls they mismatch again. Therefore it should be more correct to think they sing for their territory, sending a message to other pairs, instead of being a communication between them.
In response to playback of Tengmalms owl.

The recording has not been manipulated in any way. It was dark with only half-moon in the sky so the birds were not seen. Habitat is a mixed forest of coniferous and broadleaved trees with some wetland. The recording was made with a nest camera set up at a white-tailed eagle's nest on top of a 25 m-tall spruce.

Recording is not modified in any way. Habitat is a mixed forest with coniferous and broadleaved trees and some wetland. The recording is made from a nest camera installed at a white-tailed sea eagle's nest which is located 25 m above the ground on the top of a spruce with broken crown.

It was night and quite dark so the birds were not seen. The owls were not very near and the wind was rather loud at times. Tawny owls, both male and female, had been calling frequently in the area all winter.

recordings.loc: St James Park,City of Westminster (near  London), Greater London, England
recordings.rmk:
Begging calls heard from 2 juvenille birds in tall Plane trees in St James Park between 19:15 and 20:15.  Despite it being after dusk, many members of the public were still passing through the park or sitting and talking on nearby park benches. Little traffic noise, but some noise from aircraft passing overhead. Many waterfowl present on the lake some 10-15m away and many ducks and geese calling in the background. 

Pleasant mild, dry evening with a gradually clearing sky. Hardly any breeze present.

Birds could not be seen clearly even though the trees were bare of leaves. No sign of any adult birds coming in to feed the juvenilles.
